1) What is the role of the App component in React?

The App component is usually the main root component of a React application.

Think of it as the entry point of the UI.

Its main responsibilities:

Acts as the root container

All other components are usually rendered inside it.

It is mounted to the DOM in index.js using ReactDOM.createRoot().

Controls the main layout

Navigation bar

Pages / routes

Global sections like header, footer, sidebar

Holds global state (sometimes)

Authentication state

Theme (dark/light mode)

Global data shared between components

Organizes the component tree

Splits the UI into smaller reusable components.

Example structure:

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Navbar />
      <HomePage />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}


So the App component is basically the main parent component that starts the whole interface.

2) Why do we use a key when rendering a list?

When React renders lists, it needs a way to identify each item uniquely.

That’s where the key comes in.

Example list rendering:

const users = ["Ali", "Sara", "Omar"];

function App() {
  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map((user, index) => (
        <li key={index}>{user}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}

Why keys are important

React uses a process called Reconciliation (virtual DOM comparison).

When the list changes (add / delete / reorder), React compares:

Old list vs New list

Without keys, React can’t know which item changed.

With keys, React can:

Update only the changed item

Avoid re-rendering the whole list

Improve performance

Prevent UI bugs

Example problem without keys

Old list:

[A, B, C]


New list:

[B, C, D]


Without keys → React may think:

A changed to B

B changed to C

C changed to D
(re-render everything ❌)

With keys → React knows:

A removed ✔

D added ✔

B and C unchanged ✔

Important rule

Keys must be:

Unique

Stable (don’t change every render)

Best key:

key={user.id}   // from database


Avoid:

key={index} // only use if list never changes order


Summary

Concept	Purpose
App Component	Root of the UI and component tree
key prop	Helps React efficiently update lists and prevent bugs